For anyone out there I managed to find a solution for my problem and thought it would be better shared in case anyone else runs into the same issue. So after researching and playing around I managed to style majority of the divisions via css by using the following elements to make the border 0. 

    div[class^=&quot;col&quot;]

With this you can specify the first column, last column even numbered ones. Therefore I was able to switch the border on and off for specific divisions. 

I would say my solution was a lot more complex, as having things shift upwards or sideways depending if data is missing created more issues for the user. What we eventually decided was to have left and right cols as per our previous attempt but have it so we can balance both the left and right rows. So if we had 8 rows in total there would be 4 in each. If we had 9 then 5 in the left and 4 in the right and so on. 

I did this by adding a left and right repeater to repeat the rows from our first attempt and in code had the following to split the datatable in two. 

     int totalRows = dt.Rows.Count;
     int halfway = (int)Math.Ceiling((float)totalRows / 2);
     LeftDataTable = dt.AsEnumerable().Take(halfway).CopyToDataTable();
     RightDataTable = dt.AsEnumerable().Skip(halfway).Take(totalRows - halfway).CopyToDataTable(); 

Using this I can now add it to our repeater, so regardless of how many rows we have in total to show it will always balance out the  the left and right columns.

